The '''''Records of the Grand Historian''''',<!--Chinese in infobox; see WP:MOS-ZH--> also known by its [[Chinese language|Chinese]] name '''''Shiji''''', is a monumental [[Chinese historiography|history of ancient China]] and the world finished around 94 BC by the [[Han dynasty]] official [[Sima Qian]] after having been started by his father, [[Sima Tan]], Grand Astrologer to the imperial court. The work covers the world as it was then known to the Chinese and a 2500-year period from the age of the legendary [[Yellow Emperor]] to the reign of [[Emperor Wu of Han]] in the author's own time.{{sfnb|Nienhauser|2011|pp = [https://books.google.com/books?id=pYM3AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA486&dq=Historiography+Chinese+shiji&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zFVIVJyXMoSTyASojYHoDw&ved=0CE0Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Shiji&f=false 463-464]}}

The ''Records'' has been called a "foundational text in Chinese civilization".{{sfnp|Hardy|1999|p=xiii}} After [[Confucius]] and the [[Qin Shi Huang|First Emperor of Qin]], "Sima Qian was one of the creators of Imperial China, not least because by providing definitive biographies, he virtually created the two earlier figures."{{sfnp|Hardy|1999|pp=xiii, 3}}  The ''Records'' set the model for the 24 subsequent [[Twenty-Four Histories|dynastic histories of China]]. In contrast to Western historical works, the ''Records'' do not treat history as "a continuous, sweeping narrative", but rather break it up into smaller, overlapping units dealing with famous leaders, individuals, and major topics of significance.{{sfnp|Durrant|1986|p=689}}

==History==
{{further|Chinese historiography}}
The work that became ''Records of the Grand Historian'' was begun by [[Sima Tan]], the Grand Astrologer (''Taishi'' {{lang|zh|太史}}) of the [[Han dynasty]] court during the late 2nd century{{sbc}}. After his death in 110{{sbc}}, it was continued and completed by his son and successor [[Sima Qian]], who is generally credited as the work's author.{{sfnp|Hulsewé|1993|pp=405-06}}{{sfnp|Durrant|2001|pp=502-03}}  Sima Qian is known to have completed the ''Records'' before his death in c. 86{{sbc}}, with one copy residing in the imperial capital of [[Chang'an]] (modern [[Xi'an]]) and the other copy probably being stored in his home.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=897}}  

Details of the ''Records''{{apostrophe}} early reception and circulation are not well known.{{sfnp|Kern|2010|p=102}}  A number of 1st century BC authors, such as the scholar Chu Shaosun ({{lang|zh|褚少孫}}; fl. 32{{ndash}}7{{sbc}}), added interpolations to the ''Records'', and may have had to reconstruct portions of it: ten of the original 130 chapters were lost in the Eastern Han period (AD 25{{ndash}}220) and seem to have been reconstructed later.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=897}}

Beginning in the [[Northern and Southern dynasties]] (420{{ndash}}589) and the [[Tang dynasty]] (607{{ndash}}918), a number of scholars wrote and edited commentaries to the ''Records''.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=897}}  Most 1st millennium editions of the ''Records'' include the commentaries of Pei Yin ({{lang|zh|裴駰}}, 5th century), [[Sima Zhen]] (early 8th century), and Zhang Shoujie ({{lang|zh|張守節}}, early 8th century).{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=898}}{{sfnp|Hulsewé|1993|p=407}}  The primary modern edition of the ''Records'' is the [[Zhonghua Book Company]] edition of 1959 (revised in 1982), and is based on an edition prepared by the Chinese historian [[Gu Jiegang]] in the early 1930s.{{sfnp|Hulsewé|1993|p=409}}

===Manuscripts===
There are two known surviving fragments of ''Records'' manuscripts from before the Tang dynasty, both of which are preserved in the [[Ishiyama-dera]] temple in [[Ōtsu|Ōtsu, Japan]].  Portions of at least nine Tang dynasty manuscripts survive: three fragments discovered among the [[Dunhuang manuscripts]] in the early 20th century, and six manuscripts preserved in Japanese temples and museums, such as the [[Kōzan-ji]] temple in [[Kyoto]] and the [[Tōyō Bunko]] museum in [[Tokyo]].  A number of woodblock printed editions of the ''Records'' survive, the earliest of which date to the [[Song dynasty]] (960{{ndash}}1297).{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=898}}

==Contents==
{{see also|List of Records of the Grand Historian chapters}}

In all, the ''Records'' is about 526,000 [[Chinese characters]] long, making it four times longer than [[Thucydides]]' ''[[History of the Peloponnesian War]]'' and longer than the [[Old Testament]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hardy |first=Grant |title=Can an Ancient Chinese Historian Contribute to Modern Western Theory? The Multiple Narratives of Ssu-Ma Ch'ien |journal=History and Theory |year=1994 |volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=20–38 |jstor=2505650}}</ref>{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=708}}

Sima Qian conceived and composed his work in self-contained units, with a good deal of repetition between them. His manuscript was written on [[bamboo slips]] with about 24 to 36 characters each, and assembled into bundles of around 30 slips. Even after the manuscript was allowed to circulate or be copied, the work would have circulated as bundles of bamboo slips or small groups. [[Endymion Wilkinson]] calculates that there were probably between 466 and 700 bundles, whose total weight would have been {{Convert|88|-|132|lb|kg}}, which would have been difficult to access and hard to transport. Later copies on silk would have been much lighter, but also expensive and rare. Until the work was transferred to paper many centuries later, circulation would have been difficult and piecemeal, which accounts for many of the errors and variations in the text.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=708}}

Sima Qian organized the chapters of ''Records of the Grand Historian'' into five categories, which each comprise a section of the book.

; Basic Annals
: The "Basic Annals" (''běnjì'' {{lang|zh|本紀}}) make up the first 12 chapters of the ''Records'', and are largely similar to records from the ancient Chinese court chronicle tradition, such as the ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals]]''.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} The first five cover either periods, such as the [[Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors#Five Emperors|Five Emperors]], or individual dynasties, such as the [[Xia dynasty|Xia]], [[Shang dynasty|Shang]], and [[Zhou dynasty|Zhou]] dynasties.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}  The last seven cover individual rulers, starting with the [[Qin Shi Huang|First Emperor of Qin]] and progressing through the first emperors of the [[Han dynasty]].{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} In this section, Sima chose to also include ''de facto'' rulers of China, such as [[Xiang Yu]] and [[Empress Lü Zhi|Empress Dowager Lü]], while excluding rulers who never held any real power, such as [[Emperor Yi of Chu]] and [[Emperor Hui of Han]].{{sfnp|Watson|1958|pp=111–112}}
; Tables
: Chapters 13 to 22 are the "Tables" (''biǎo'' {{lang|zh|表}}), which are one genealogical table and nine other chronological tables.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}  They show reigns, important events, and royal lineages in table form, which Sima Qian stated that he did because "the chronologies are difficult to follow when different genealogical lines exist at the same time."<ref>''Shiji'' 130: 3319, cited in {{harvp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}.</ref> Each table except the last one begins with an introduction to the period it covers.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}
; Treatises
: The "Treatises" (''shū'' {{lang|zh|書}}, sometimes called "Monographs") is the shortest of the five ''Records'' sections, and contains eight chapters (23&ndash;30) on the historical evolution of ritual, music, [[pitch pipe]]s, the calendar, astronomy, sacrifices, rivers and waterways, and financial administration.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}
; Hereditary Houses
: The "Hereditary Houses" (''shìjiā'' {{lang|zh|世家}}) is the second largest of the five ''Records'' sections, and comprises chapters 31 to 60. Within this section, the earlier chapters are very different in nature than the later chapters.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} Many of the earlier chapters are chronicle-like accounts of the leading states of the [[Zhou dynasty]], such as the states of [[Qin (state)|Qin]] and [[Lu (state)|Lu]], and two of the chapters go back as far as the [[Shang dynasty]].{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}  The later chapters, which cover the Han dynasty, contain biographies.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}
; Ranked Biographies
: The "Ranked Biographies" (''lièzhuàn'' {{lang|zh|列傳}}, usually shortened to "Biographies") is the largest of the five ''Records'' sections, covering chapters 61 to 130, and accounts for 42% of the entire work.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} The 69 "Biographies" chapters mostly contain biographical profiles of about 130 outstanding ancient Chinese men, ranging from the moral paragon [[Boyi and Shuqi|Boyi]] from the end of the Shang dynasty to some of Sima Qian's near contemporaries.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} About 40 of the chapters are dedicated to one particular man, but some are about two related figures, while others cover small groups of figures who shared certain roles, such as assassins, caring officials, or Confucian scholars.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} Unlike most modern biographies, the accounts in the "Biographies" give profiles using anecdotes to depict morals and character, with "unforgettably lively impressions of people of many different kinds and of the age in which they lived."{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}} The "Biographies" have been popular throughout Chinese history, and have provided a large number of set phrases still used in modern Chinese.{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2012|p=706}}

==Style==
[[File:Sima Qian (painted portrait).jpg|thumb|Sima Qian]]

Unlike subsequent official historical texts that adopted [[Confucian]] doctrine, proclaimed the divine rights of the emperors, and degraded any failed claimant to the throne, Sima Qian's more liberal and objective prose has been renowned and followed by poets and novelists. Most volumes of ''Liezhuan'' are vivid descriptions of events and persons. Sima Qian sought out stories from those who might have closer knowledge of certain historical events, using them as sources to balance the reliability and accuracy of historical records. For instance, the material on [[Jing Ke]]'s attempt at assassinating the [[Qin Shi Huang|King of Qin]] incorporates an eye-witness account by Xia Wuju ({{lang|zh|夏無且}}), a physician to the king of [[Qin (state)|Qin]] who happened to be attending the diplomatic ceremony for Jing Ke, and this account was passed on to Sima Qian by those who knew Xia.{{sfnp|Watson|1958|pp=191, 240}}

It has been observed that the diplomatic Sima Qian has a way of accentuating the positive in his treatment of rulers in the Basic Annals, but slipping negative information into other chapters, and so his work must be read as a whole to obtain full information. For example, the information that [[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Liu Bang]] (later Emperor Gaozu of Han), in a desperate attempt to escape in a chase from [[Xiang Yu]]'s men, pushed his own children off his carriage to lighten it, was not given in the emperor's biography, but in the biography of Xiang Yu. He is also careful to balance the negative with the positive, for example, in the biography of [[Empress Lü Zhi|Empress Dowager Lu]] which contains lurid accounts of her cruelty, he pointed out at the end that, despite whatever her personal life may have been, her rule brought peace and prosperity to the country.{{sfnp|Watson|1958|pp=95–98}}

==Source materials==
Sima's family were hereditary historians to the Han emperor. Sima Qian's father [[Sima Tan]] served as Grand Historian, and Sima Qian succeeded to his position. Thus he had access to the early Han dynasty archives, edicts, and records. Sima Qian was a methodical, skeptical historian who had access to ancient books, written on [[bamboo and wooden slips]], from before the time of the Han dynasty. Many of the sources he used did not survive. He not only used archives and imperial records, but also interviewed people and traveled around China to verify information. In his first chapter, "Annals of the Five Emperors," he writes,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctext.org/shiji/wu-di-ben-ji |title=Annals of the Five Emperors |script-title=zh:五帝本紀 |publisher=Chinese Text Project |website=ctext.org |quote={{lang|zh|余嘗西至空桐，北過涿鹿，東漸於海，南浮江淮矣，至長老皆各往往稱黃帝、堯、舜之處，風教固殊焉，總之不離古文者近是。}}}}</ref>

{{quote|I myself have travelled west as far as [[Kongtong Mountains|K'ung-t'ung]], north past [[Zhuolu Town|Cho-lu]], east to the sea, and in the south I have sailed the [[Yellow River|Yellow]] and [[Huai River]]s. The elders and old men of these various lands frequently pointed out to me the places where the [[Yellow Emperor]], [[Emperor Yao|Yao]], and [[Shun (Chinese leader)|Shun]] had lived, and in these places the manners and customs seemed quite different. In general those of their accounts which do not differ from the ancient texts seem to be near to the truth. |Sima Qian, translation by [[Burton Watson]]{{sfnp|Watson|1958|p=183}}}}

The Grand Historian used ''The Annals of the Five Emperors'' ({{lang|zh|五帝系諜}}) and the ''[[Classic of History]]'' as source materials to make genealogies from the time of the [[Yellow Emperor]] until that of the [[Gonghe (regency)|Gonghe regency]] (841-828 BC). Sima Qian often cites his sources. For example, in the first chapter, "Annals of the Five Emperors", he writes, "I have read the ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals]]'' and the ''[[Guoyu (book)|Guoyu]]''." In his 13th chapter, "Genealogical Table of the Three Ages," Sima Qian writes, "I have read all the genealogies of the kings (''dieji'' {{lang|zh|谍记}}) that exist since the time of the Yellow Emperor." In his 14th chapter, "Yearly Chronicle of the Feudal Lords", he writes, "I have read all the royal annals (''chunqiu li pudie'' {{lang|zh|春秋曆譜諜}}) up until the time of [[King Li of Zhou]]." In his 15th chapter, "Yearly Chronicle of the Six States," he writes, “I have read the Annals of [[Qin (state)|Qin]] (''qin ji'' {{lang|zh|秦記}}), and they say that the [[Quanrong]] [a barbarian tribe] defeated [[King You of Zhou]] [ca 771 BC]."

In the 19th chapter, he writes, "I have occasion to read over the records of enfeoffment and come to the case of Wu Qian, the marquis of Bian...." (The father of Marquis Bian, Wu Rui, was named king (wang) of [[Changsha]] in [[Hunan]] for his loyalty to Gaozu. See article on [[Zhao Tuo]]). In his chapter on the patriotic minister and poet [[Qu Yuan]], Sima Qian writes, "I have read [Qu Yuan's works] ''[[Li Sao]]'', ''[[Tianwen]]'' ("Heaven Asking"), ''Zhaohun'' (summoning the soul), and ''Ai Ying'' ([[Lament for Ying]])". In the 62nd chapter, "Biography of Guan and of Yan", he writes, "I have read Guan's ''Mu Min'' ({{lang|zh|牧民}} - "Government of the People", a chapter in the ''[[Guanzi (text)|Guanzi]]''), ''Shan Gao'' ("The Mountains Are High"), ''Chengma'' ([[chariot]] and horses; a long section on war and economics), ''Qingzhong'' (Light and Heavy; i.e. "what is important"), and ''Jiufu'' (Nine Houses), as well as the ''Spring and Autumn Annals of Yanzi''." In his 64th chapter, "Biography of [[Sima Rangju]]", the Grand Historian writes, "I have read Sima's Art of War." In the 121st chapter, "Biographies of Scholars", he writes, "I read the Imperial Decrees that encouraged education officials."
[[File:Records of the Grand Historian.jpg|thumb|Chapter 2, ''Annals of Xia'' (Ming dynasty edition)]]

Sima Qian wrote of the problems with incomplete, fragmentary and contradictory sources. For example, he mentioned in the preface to chapter 15 that the chronicle records of the feudal states kept in the [[Zhou dynasty]]'s archive were burnt by [[Qin Shi Huang]] because they contained criticisms and ridicule of the Qin state, and that the Qin annals were brief and incomplete.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ctext.org/shiji/liu-guo-nian-biao#n5146 |trans-title=Chronological table of the six kingdoms |script-title=zh:六國年表 |publisher=Chinese Text Project |website=ctext.org |quote={{lang|zh|秦既得意，燒天下詩書，諸侯史記尤甚，為其有所刺譏也。詩書所以復見者，多藏人家，而史記獨藏周室，以故滅。惜哉，惜哉！獨有秦記，又不載日月，其文略不具。}}}}</ref> In the 13th chapter he mentioned that the chronologies and genealogies of different ancient texts "disagree and contradict each other throughout". In his 18th chapter, Sima Qian writes, "I have set down only what is certain, and in doubtful cases left a blank."<ref>''Records of the Grand Historian'', vol. ''Han Dynasty I'', translated by [[Burton Watson]] (Columbia University, Revised Edition, 1993)</ref>

==Reliability and accuracy==
Scholars have questioned the historicity of legendary kings of the ancient periods given by Sima Qian. Sima Qian began the ''Shiji'' with an account of the five rulers of supreme virtue, the [[Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors|Five Emperors]], who modern scholars, such as those from the [[Doubting Antiquity School]], believe to be originally local deities of the peoples of ancient China.{{sfnp|Watson|1958|pp=16–17}}  Sima Qian sifted out the elements of the supernatural and fantastic which seemed to contradict their existence as actual human monarchs, and was therefore criticized for turning myths and folklore into sober history.{{sfnp|Watson|1958|pp=16–17}}

However, according to [[Joseph Needham]], who wrote in 1954 on Sima Qian's accounts of the kings of the [[Shang dynasty]] (c. 1600&ndash;c. 1050 BC): {{quote|It was commonly maintained that Ssuma Chhien [Sima Qian] could not have adequate historical materials for his account of what had happened more than a thousand years earlier. One may judge of the astonishment of many, therefore, when it appeared that no less than twenty-three of the thirty rulers' name were to be clearly found on the indisputably genuine [[Anyang]] [[oracle bones|bones]]. It must be, therefore, that Ssuma Chhien [Sima Qian] did have fairly reliable materials at his disposal—a fact which underlines once more the deep historical-mindedness of the Chinese—and that the Shang dynasty is perfectly acceptable.|Joseph Needham<ref name=needham>{{cite book |author=Needham, Joseph. |year=1954 |title=Science and Civilization in China: Volume 1, Introductory Orientations |publisher= Cambridge University Press  |isbn=0-521-05799-X  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lNXZGQVdz_gC&pg=PA88&lpg=PA88&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |page=88 }}</ref>}}

While some aspects of Sima Qian's history of the Shang dynasty are supported by inscriptions on the oracle bones, there is, as yet, no clear corroborating evidence from archaeology on Sima Qian's history of the [[Xia dynasty]].

There are also discrepancies of fact such as dates between various portions of the work. This may be a result of Sima Qian's use of different source texts.{{sfnp|Watson|1958|p=113}}

==Transmission and supplementation by other writers==
After ca. 91 BC, the more-or-less completed manuscript was hidden in the residence of the author's daughter, Sima Ying ({{lang|zh|司馬英}}), to avoid destruction under [[Emperor Wu of Han|Emperor Wu]] and his immediate successor [[Emperor Zhao of Han|Emperor Zhao]]. The ''Shiji'' was finally disseminated during the reign of [[Emperor Xuan of Han|Emperor Xuan]] by Sima Qian's grandson (through his daughter), Yang Yun ({{lang|zh|楊惲}}), after a hiatus of around twenty years.

The changes in the manuscript of the ''Shiji'' during this hiatus have always been disputed among scholars. That the text was more or less complete by ca. 91 BC is established in the Letter to Ren'an ({{lang|zh|報任安書}}), composed in the Zhenghe ({{lang|zh|征和}}) era of Emperor Wu's reign.  In this letter, Sima Qian describes his work as "spanning from the time of the Yellow Emperor to the present age and consisting of ten tables, twelve basic annals, eight treatises, thirty chapters on hereditary houses, and seventy biographies, together totaling 130 chapters."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/%E5%A0%B1%E4%BB%BB%E5%B0%91%E5%8D%BF%E6%9B%B8 |trans-title=Letter to Ren'an |script-title=zh:報任少卿書 |lang=zh |website=Wikisource |quote={{lang|zh|報任少卿書：『上計軒轅，下至于茲，為十表，本紀十二，書八章，世家三十，列傳七十，凡百三十篇。』}}}}</ref>  These numbers are likewise given in the postface to ''Shiji''.{{sfnp|Watson|1958|pp=56–67}}

After his death (presumably only a few years later), few people had the opportunity to see the whole work. However, various additions were still made to it. The historian [[Liu Zhiji]] reported the names of a total of fifteen scholars supposed to have added material to the ''Shiji'' during the period after the death of Sima Qian. Only the additions by Chu Shaosun ({{lang|zh|褚少孫}}, c.105 - c.30 BC) are clearly indicated by adding "Mr Chu said," (Chu xiansheng yue, {{lang|zh|褚先生曰}}). Already in the first century AD, [[Ban Biao]] and [[Ban Gu]] claimed that ten chapters in ''Records of the Grand Historian'' were lacking. <!--must have been completed later .--> A large number of chapters dealing with the first century of the Han dynasty (i.e. the 2nd century BC) correspond exactly to the relevant chapters from the ''[[Book of Han]]'' (''Hanshu''). It is unclear whether those chapters initially came from the ''Shiji'' or from the ''Hanshu''. Researchers Yves Hervouet (1921-1999) and [[A.F.P. Hulsewé]] argued that the originals of those chapters of the ''Shiji'' were lost and they were later reconstructed using the corresponding chapters from the ''Hanshu''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Hulsewé, A. F. P. |year=1979 |title=China in Central Asia: The Early Stage 125 BC – AD 23: an annotated translation of chapters 61 and 96 of the History of the Former Han Dynasty |publisher=E. Brill, Leiden |pages=8–25 |isbn=90-04-05884-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HzhCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>

==Editions==
The earliest extant copy of ''Records of the Grand Historian'', handwritten, was made during the [[Southern and Northern Dynasties]] period (420 – 589 AD). The earliest printed edition, called ''Shiji jijie'' ({{lang|zh|史記集解}}, literally ''Records of the Grand Historian, Collected Annotations''), was published during the [[Northern Song dynasty]]. [[Huang Shanfu]]'s edition, printed under the [[Southern Song dynasty]], is the earliest collection of the ''Sanjiazhu'' commentaries on ''Records of the Grand Historian'' ({{lang|zh|三家注}}, literally: ''The Combined Annotations of the Three Experts'').

In modern times, the [[Zhonghua Book Company]] in [[Beijing]] has published the book in both [[simplified Chinese]] and [[traditional Chinese]] editions. The 1959 (2nd ed., 1982) ''Sanjiazhu'' edition (based upon the Jinling Publishing House edition, ''vide infra'') contains commentaries interspersed among the main text and is considered to be an authoritative modern edition.

The most well known [[rare book|editions]] of the ''Shiji'' are:
